solution.p:
Using the angle \theta = 30^{\circ} with respect to Ox direction, we can determine the x- and y-components, (F_x,F_y) of the given vector \vec F.

	 \amp 
		F_x = (20\ \text{N})\ \cos(30^{\circ}) = 17 \ \text{N}

	 \amp 
		F_y = (20\ \text{N})\ \sin(30^{\circ}) = 10 \ \text{N}


Similarly, using the angle \theta' = 40^{\circ} with respect to Ox' direction, we can determine the x- and y-components, (F_x',F_y') of the given vector \vec F.

	 \amp 
		F_x' = (20\ \text{N})\ \cos(40^{\circ}) =15  \ \text{N}

	 \amp 
		F_y' = (20\ \text{N})\ \sin(40^{\circ}) = 13 \ \text{N}

sidebyside.p:
We want a vector  \hat u  of unit magnitude in the direction described. We need to just find its x and  y  components.

	 \amp u_x = 1\times \cos\, 30^{\circ} = \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
	 \amp u_x = 1\times \sin\, 30^{\circ} = \dfrac{1}{2}.

solution.p:
The angle using the arctangent formula gives the following.

		 \theta \amp = \tan^{-1} \dfrac{A_y}{A_x} 
		 \amp = \tan^{-1}\dfrac{1}{-3} = -18.4^{\circ}.
